==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Finance
<hw>Fi*nance"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL.
<ets>financia</ets> payment of money, money, fr. <ets>finare</ets> to
pay a fine or subsidy (cf. OF. <ets>finer</ets> to finish, pay), fr. L.
<ets>finis</ets> end. See <er>Fine</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Finish</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The income of a ruler or of a
state; revenue; public money; sometimes, the income of an individual;
often used in the plural for funds; available money;
resources.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>finances</qex> or revenues of the imperial crown.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The science of raising and expending the public
revenue.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Versed in the details of
<xex>finance</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Finance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Finance
<hw>Fi*nance"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Financed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Financing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To
conduct the finances of; to provide for, and manage, the capital for; to
financier.</def></p>

<p><q>Securing foreign capital to <qex>finance</qex> multitudinous
undertakings.</q> <rj><qau>B. H. Chamberlain.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>finances</ent>⟦br⟧
